  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">NIHR Global Research Professorships: Preventing Invasive Salmonella Disease in Africa</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The NIHR Global Research Professorship scheme is open to all professions and all Higher Education Institutions (HEI), based in England and the Devolved Administrations, to nominate health researchers and methodologists with an outstanding research record of clinical and applied health research and its effective translation for improved health. Global Research Professors are required to have existing strong collaborations or links with collaborators or partners in institutions in countries on the OECD DAC list and the award should plan to strengthen these/support training and capacity development/mentorship in these partners. Typhoid fever and Invasive Non-Typhoidal Salmonella (iNTS) disease are two invasive blood-stream infections caused by bacteria called Salmonella responsible for serious illness and death particularly in young children in sub-Saharan Africa. This research aims to drive translational impact in the prevention of invasive Salmonella disease in Africa, with the major focus on accelerating and advancing the national and regional introduction of vaccination for Typhoid and for iNTS disease. The project is based in Malawi and the majority of the research will be conducted in this region.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To accelerate the vaccine prevention of Typhoid fever and Invasive Non-Typhoidal Salmonella disease. The research has 3 workstreams: 1.) Epidemiology: how much typhoid and iNTS disease are happening, and how do they spread in urban and rural communities? 2.) Protection: How do people&#x2019;s bodies make protective immune responses against Salmonella infection, and how can we design better vaccines? 3.) Vaccines: How well do the vaccines actually work in healthy and immunosuppressed children? In addition Professor Gordon will support these workstreams with activities to discuss and explain Salmonella disease and research among the communities she works with, use research findings to engage with stakeholders and accelerated introduction of vaccines, and train the next generation of doctors and scientists in Malawi to be the researchers of the future.</narrative>
  </description>
